      <trans-unit id="14567" identifier="1a12f1ada4b928009de01b455c45e30e">
        <source>The diagram above shows a circle (radius 100) drawn using the Pythagoras’ Theorem method.
(Note: The red triangle inside the circle is only to show the calculation and does not need to be drawn).</source>
        <target>crwdns14567:0crwdne14567:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="14568" identifier="6c3a5abf71d5c3c5bd7e1a212123d8d1">
        <source>You can use Pythagoras’ Theorem (in any right-angle triangle, the square of the side opposite the right angle is equal to the sum of the squares of the other two sides so here \( x^{2}+y^{2}=radius^{2}\)) to draw a circle.</source>
        <target>crwdns14568:0{2}crwdnd14568:0{2}crwdnd14568:0{2}crwdne14568:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="14569" identifier="0e06e1eb8af46330282dbc99b670d203">
        <source>We can do this by rearranging the formula to solve for \(y\) like this:</source>
        <target>crwdns14569:0crwdne14569:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="14570" identifier="c45168750df0a99494a5d6d61fd21ffc">
        <source>\[
  y^{2} = radius ^{2} - x^{2} \\
  y = sqrt{(radius^{2} - x^{2})}&lt;br /&gt;
\]</source>
        <target>crwdns14570:0{2}crwdnd14570:0{2}crwdnd14570:0{2}crwdnd14570:0{2}crwdnd14570:0{2}crwdne14570:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[7]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="14571" identifier="3f3766e86e0903fbe767fecbe99191eb">
        <source>We then calculate \(y\) using a range of values for \(x\) (i.e. from 0 to \(\pm radius\)).</source>
        <target>crwdns14571:0crwdne14571:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[8]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="14572" identifier="6179664ae6387edb35a4fcc4df168a4e">
        <source>Your programming language will probably only give you the positive square root, so you will also need to plot the negative of \(y\).</source>
        <target>crwdns14572:0crwdne14572:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[8]</note>
      </trans-unit>
